new, politically relevant era for Protestantism. Focusing on everyday practices--praying for Guatemala, speaking in tongues for the soul of the nation, organizing prayer campaigns to combat unprecedented levels of crime--O'Neill finds that Christian citizenship has re-politicized the faithful as they struggle to understand what it means to be a believer in a desperately violent Central American city. Innovative, imaginative, conceptually rich, City of God reaches across disciplinary borders as it illuminates the highly charged, evolving relationship between religion, democracy, and the state in Latin America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChristianity and politicszGuatemalazGuatemala. 0aEvangelistic workxPentecostal churches. 0aEvangelistic workzGuatemalazGuatemala. 0aPentecostal churchesxMissionszGuatemalazGuatemala. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / General.2bisacsh  abelief system.  acentral america.  achristian charity.  achristian citizenship.  achristian soldier.  achristianity.  achristians.  acitizenship.  acounterinsurgency.  acrime.  acultural studies.  ademocracy.  adiaspora.  agod and religion.  agovernment and government.  aguatemala city.  aguatemala.  aguatemalan culture.  alatin american culture.  amega churches.  aneo pentecostal christian practices.  apolitical studies.  apolitical.  apolitics.  apostwar.  aprayer campaigns.  aprayer.  aprotestantism.  areligion.  areligious studies.  aspiritual warfare.  atransnational studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052026062740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094513540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520945135423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/97805209